nevertheless a political necessity.=20
They are not inclined to make the wrenching changes needed reducing non-meri=
t=20
subsidies and surplus staff, while increasing the collection of taxes and=20
user charges.=20
The quality of public services keeps deteriorating, which is why ruling=20
parties keep losing elections. What election pundits call the anti-incumbenc=
y=20
factor is simply unrepentant non-performance.=20
This has been institutionalised since every outgoing regime believes that th=
e=20
other side will fail to perform too, letting it return to power unreformed.=20
For many decades of planned development, the private sector was perceived to=
=20
have little money while governments were perceived to have very deep pockets=
=2E=20
The very opposite is true today. State governments are bust, and cannot=20
deliver even basic services like primary education and health.=20
Meanwhile, the private sector is able to take up the biggest projects ever.=20
Reliance has just built the biggest oil refinery in the world with no=20
government assistance at all. Individuals today shell out Rs 20 lakh or more=
=20
for luxury cars, but governments departments cannot afford even Ambassador=20
cars.=20
